Atmospheric dispersion modeling was performed using the RMP*Comp program distributed by the Chemical Emergency Preparedness and Prevention Office of the United States Environmental Protection Agency (USEPA).  This model determined the distance traveled by chlorine and sodium dioxide released until concentrations decrease to the "toxic endpoint" of 0.0087 milligrams per Liter (mg/L) and 0.0078 mg/L, respectively, as selected by USEPA.  The chlorine toxic endpoint of 0.0087 mg/L in air and sulfur dioxide toxic endpoint of 0.0078 mg/L in air both represent the American Industrial Hygiene Association (AIHA) Emergency Response Planning Guideline (ERPG)-2, defined as the A?maximum airborne concentration below which it is believed that nearly all individuals could be exposed for up to 1 hour without experiencing or developing irreversible or other serious health effects or symptoms which could impair an individual=s ability to take protective actionA?.  These amount corresponds to 3.0 parts per million by volume.   

The Hanover WWTP accidental release prevention program is based upon the following elements:

1.    High level of training for the operators;

2.    Preventative maintenance program for equipment;

3.    Use of state-of-the-art process and safety equipment;

4.    Use of accurate and effective standard operating procedures, written with the participation of the operators;

5.    Performance of a Hazard Review of the equipment and procedures; and

6.    Implementation of an auditing and inspection program.

Chemical specific prevention steps include availability of self contained breathing apparatus, awareness of the hazards and toxic properties of chlorine and sulfur dioxide, and the presence of gas detectors.

